<!--
  wazuh-home (manager): custom dnsmasq query-line decoder.

  Append inside /var/ossec/etc/decoders/local_decoder.xml on the manager.
  After editing, validate + restart:
      sudo /var/ossec/bin/wazuh-analysisd -t   # parse-only, no daemon start
      sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager

  Why this exists: Wazuh's stock ruleset does NOT ship a dnsmasq
  decoder, despite Pi-hole emitting standard dnsmasq syntax. Without it
  the agent ships every line, the manager parses the syslog header but
  the message body falls through and lands in archives.json with
  decoder.name = NO_DECODER. No fields, no rule chain, no alerts.

  This decoder catches the lines we actually care about for
  Vault-VM-on-LAN-Pi-hole observability: the original query[*] lines.
  We deliberately don't decode forwarded / reply / cached / gravity
  blocked because those don't carry the client srcip and adding them
  would just generate duplicate events without extra signal.

  Matches lines like:
      May  1 15:00:32 dnsmasq[52]: query[A] github.com from 192.168.50.3
      May  1 15:00:32 dnsmasq[52]: query[AAAA] api.cloudflare.com from 192.168.50.3
      May  1 15:00:32 dnsmasq[52]: query[HTTPS] update.code.visualstudio.com from 192.168.173.35

  Extracts: qtype, query, srcip.

  PCRE2 mode is required because Wazuh's default OS_Regex syntax
  doesn't support \d or \[. The two type="pcre2" attributes are
  load-bearing; without them analysisd refuses to load with a "Syntax
  error on regex" critical.
-->
<decoder name="pihole-dnsmasq-query">
  <prematch type="pcre2">dnsmasq\[\d+\]: query\[</prematch>
  <regex type="pcre2">dnsmasq\[\d+\]: query\[(\w+)\] (\S+) from (\S+)</regex>
  <order>qtype, query, srcip</order>
</decoder>
